snippet.textDisplay: SUGGESTION FOR A FUTURE TOPIC. My mother had a mini-stroke back in 2004. By the time the doctors examined her brain the clot had moved on. They checked for possible sources of the clot and found out that she has left-ventricular non-compaction. This is apparently a deformity typically found in newborn babies. The pediatric cardiologist (Dr. Lau at UAB) who sees her for it wanted to check me and my two brothers. They didn’t have it, but I do. I was 12 at the time and it was so slight that they needed to do an MRI to see it. A year or so later it had gotten as bad as my mom’s (they could see it with an ultrasound). Anyway, I always have to mention it (and my interrupted Inferior Vena Cava with Azygous Continuation, which they found on one of my follow up MRIs) to nurses and doctors when I go to a new office. I always end up having to explain it to them because most have never heard of LVNP. Typically, newborns need a heart transplant in order to survive. Our doctor thinks adults with it live normal lives and it goes undetected. I haven’t been able to find any literature about adults with it. I was curious what you thought and if you had heard of it. (Just FYI, my mom is doing fine. I’m not on any meds for it anymore. I was on a low-dose aspirin, but that was causing other problems)

snippet.textDisplay: Kind of wish it was easier to tell if you have it since I've been having sighing Dyspnea for a couple months now. It's like I feel really aware of my breathing and thus I constantly feel like I'm probably not getting enough air. But all in all, I dont smoke anything and I eat healthily.
